''For the defunct Toronto radio station see [[CFCA (AM)]]'' {{Infobox radio station | name = CFCA-FM | image = Virgin Radio Kitchener.png | city = [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Ontario]] | area = [[Waterloo Regional Municipality|Waterloo Region]] | branding = 105.3 Virgin Radio | slogan = Kitchener's #1 Hit Music Station | airdate = 1949 | frequency = 105.3 [[MHz]] ([[FM radio|FM]]) | erp = 100 [[kilowatt|kW]]s | haat = {{convert|250|meters}} | class = C1 | format = [[Contemporary hit radio|Top 40/CHR]] | owner = [[Bell Media]] | sister_stations = [[CKKW-FM]], [[CKCO-DT]] | licensee = [[Bell Media Radio]] | webcast = [http://player.kitchener.virginradio.ca Listen live] | website = [http://kitchener.virginradio.ca/ kitchener.virginradio.ca] }}
'''CFCA-FM''' is a Canadian radio station licensed to transmit from [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Ontario]] and serving the [[Waterloo Regional Municipality|Waterloo Region]] area broadcasting at 105.3 FM. The station currently plays a [[Contemporary hit radio|Top 40/CHR]] format branded as ''105.3 Virgin Radio'' and is owned by [[Bell Media]].
CFCA's studios & offices are located in [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]], and their transmitter is on [[Baden Hill]] also known as the [[Baden Tower]], just west of the Kitchener city limits.
Based on the current format, CFCA-FM competes with [[CKBT-FM]].
==History== CFCA was first launched on 106.1 FM in 1949 by local broadcaster [[Carl Pollock|Carl A. Pollock]]. It was the first FM radio station in Canada to operate independently, without an [[AM radio]] sister station. Due to the limited audience reach of FM radio at the time, however, the station left the air in 1951. Pollock subsequently launched television station [[CKCO-DT|CKCO-TV]] in 1954 and AM radio station [[CKKW-FM|CKKW]] in 1959, and then relaunched CFCA in 1967 as an [[easy listening]] station. Pollock's broadcast holdings became part of [[Electrohome]] in 1970.
CFCA and CKKW were tentatively sold in 1992 to a local consortium consisting of Jack Schoone, a former local radio announcer, and Irving Zucker, a former owner of competing stations [[CKGL]] and [[CHYM-FM]], but the deal fell through and the stations were instead acquired by [[CHUM Radio]] in 1993. By then the station had migrated from its beautiful music/easy listening sound to a brighter [[adult contemporary]] format. On August 12, 1994 at Noon, CFCA flipped to [[classic rock]] as ''105.3 Kool FM''.
During the early 2000s, the station added pop/rock songs into their playlist, and shifted towards [[Hot AC]].
[[CTVglobemedia]] became the stations' owner when it acquired CHUM Radio in [[2007 in radio|2007]], and is currently owned by [[Bell Media]] since 2011. [[Image:Kool-FM truck (Kitchener).jpg|thumb|right|View of one of the Kool FM remote vehicles]]
[[Image:CFCA-FM.png|thumb|150px|left|Former "Kool" logo (2012-2016)]] On July 26, 2016, CFCA began stunting with [[Christmas music]], while teasing a change to come that Friday (July 29) at Noon. At that time, CFCA flipped to [[Contemporary Hit Radio|Top 40/CHR]], branded as ''105.3 Virgin Radio'', making CFCA the 8th station in Canada to utilize the "Virgin Radio" branding. (At the same time as CFCA's flip, sister [[CJCH-FM]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] rebranded to "Virgin".)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=Brent|title=Kool-FM lays off staff in advance of expected format change|url=http://www.therecord.com/news-story/6786302-kool-fm-lays-off-staff-in-advance-of-expected-format-change/|publisher=Waterloo Region Record|accessdate=18 September 2016|quote=Radio industry websites RadioInsight and Puget Sound Radio both reported that the station is expected to be reborn as a Virgin Radio "contemporary hit radio" station.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/107433/kool-christmas-stunt-in-kitchener-on/|title=Kool Christmas Stunt In Kitchener ON - RadioInsight|author=|date=26 July 2016|website=radioinsight.com|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/107445/more-virgin-radio-for-canada/|title=Virgin Radio Launches In Halifax & Kitchener - RadioInsight|author=|date=29 July 2016|website=radioinsight.com|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729172858/https://twitter.com/BellMediaPR/status/759059923539988480|title=Bell Media PR on Twitter: "Bell Media Radio Extends Canada's #1 Hit Music Brand as 105.3 Becomes 105-3 Virgin Radio @VirginRadio_KW"|author=|date=29 July 2016|website=archive.org|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://formatchange.com/cfca-becomes-105-3-virgin-radio/|title=CFCA Becomes 105.3 Virgin Radio - Format Change Archive|author=|date=30 July 2016|website=formatchange.com|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> The first song on "Virgin" was "[[This Is What You Came For]]" by [[Calvin Harris]].
