The '''Holly King''' is a speculative archetype of modern studies of [[folklore]] and [[mythology]] which has been popularized in some [[Neopaganism|Neopagan]] religions. In his book ''[[The White Goddess]]'', the author [[Robert Graves]] proposed that the mythological figure of the Holly King represents one half of the year, while the other is personified by his counterpart and adversary the '''Oak King''': the two battle endlessly as the seasons turn. At [[Midsummer]] the Oak King is at the height of his strength, while the Holly King is at his weakest. The Holly King begins to regain his power, and at the Autumn Equinox, the tables finally turn in the Holly King's favor; his strength peaks at [[Winter solstice|Midwinter]]. Graves identified a number of paired hero-figures which he believes are variants of this myth, including [[Lleu Llaw Gyffes]] and [[Gronw Pebr]], [[Gwyn ap Nudd|Gwyn]] and [[Gwythr ap Greidawl|Gwythr]], [[Lugh]] and [[Balor]], [[Sir Balan|Balan]] and [[Sir Balin|Balin]], [[Gawain and the Green Knight]], the robin and the wren, and even [[Jesus]] and [[John the Baptist]].<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Robert Graves]]|title=The White Goddess; a historical grammar of poetic myth |year=1978|publisher=Octagon Books|location=New York|isbn=9780374932398}}</ref><ref name=williamson/>
A similar idea was suggested previously by [[Sir James George Frazer]] in his work ''[[The Golden Bough]]'' in Chapter XXVIII, ''The Killing of The Tree Spirit'' in the section entitled ''The Battle of Summer and Winter''.<ref name=williamson/><ref name=bough/><ref name=uu/><ref>{{cite web|author=Anna Franklin|title=Midsummer|url=http://www.merciangathering.com/coamhain.htm|publisher=merciangathering.com|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> Frazer drew parallels between the folk-customs associated with [[May Day]] or the changing seasons in [[Scandinavia]]n, [[Bavaria]]n and [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] cultures, amongst others, in support of this theory.<ref name=bough>{{cite book|author=Sir [[James George Frazer]]|title=[[The Golden Bough|The golden bough; a study in magic and religion, Volume 6]]|publisher=Macmillan|location=New York}}</ref> However the Divine King of Frazer was split into the kings of winter and summer in Graves' work.<ref name=williamson>{{cite book|author=John Williamson|title=The oak king, the holly king, and the unicorn: the myths and symbolism of the unicorn tapestries |year=1986|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York|isbn=9780060155308}}</ref><ref name=uu>{{cite web|title=Pagan Readings|url=http://www.uueugene.org/CUUPs/Readings.html|publisher=uueugene.org|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref>
These pairs are seen as the dual aspects of the male Earth deity, one ruling the waxing year, the other ruling the waning year. [[Stewart Farrar|Stewart]] and [[Janet Farrar]], following Graves' theory, gave a similar interpretation to [[Wicca]]n seasonal rituals.<ref>{{cite book|author=Farrar, Janet and Stewart|title=Eight Sabbats for Witches, revised edition|publisher=Phoenix Publishing|year=1988|isbn=0-919345-26-3}}</ref> According to Joanne Pearson, the Holly King is represented by [[holly]] and other [[evergreen]]s, and personifies the dark half of the [[Wicca]]n [[Wheel of the Year]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Joanne Pearson|title=A Popular Dictionary of Paganism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3W02UMPejRwC |year=2002|pages=80|location=London|publisher=Taylor & Francis Ltd|isbn=9780700715916}}</ref> He is also seen by some Neopagans as an early inspiration for the [[Father Christmas]] legend.<ref>{{cite book|author=Raven Grimassi |title=Encyclopedia of Wicca & Witchcraft|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kzp63ep-MlQC |year=2000|pages=219|location=St Paul, Minnesota|publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide|isbn=9781567182576}}</ref>
The battle of light with dark is commonly played out in traditional folk dance and [[mummers play]]s across Britain such as [[Calan Mai]] in Wales, [[Mazey Day]] in Cornwall and [[Jack in the Green]] traditions in England which typically include a ritual ''battle'' in some form.
