'''Sky Horse''' ({{zh|c=天馬飛彈|p=Tiānmǎ Fēidàn}}) is a ballistic missile developed secretly by [[Taiwan]] in the late 1970s, with a considerable number being produced.<ref name="taipeitimes1999">{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/1999/12/09/0000014179/1 |title=Lien says Taiwan needs new long-range missile |publisher=Taipei Times |date=2017-02-11 |accessdate=2017-02-17}}</ref>
==Development== Sky Horse was developed by the [[National Chung-Shan Institute of Science and Technology]] (CSIST), and was associated with the country's then-secret nuclear weapons program. With a range of 600-950 kilometres,<ref name="Cochran1997">{{cite book|author=Thad Cochran|title=National Missile Defense and Prospects for U.S. - Russia Abm Treaty Accommodation: Hearing Before the Committee on Governmental Affairs, U.S. Senate|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7bBALxxwpX8C&pg=PA141|date=1 June 1997|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-0-7881-8304-1|page=141}}</ref> it would have been capable of striking pre-emptively at ports, airfields or missile bases on the [[Mainland China|Mainland]] in an arc from Shanghai to Zhanjiang.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/conf_proceedings/CF137/CF137.chap9.pdf|format=PDF|title=9. CHINESE DEFENSE MODERNIZATION AND THE SECURITY OF TAIWAN|author=Gary Klintworth|website=Rand.org|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref>
==Project cancellation== The Sky Horse project was cancelled partly due to pressure from the USA, and partly so that the CSIST could concentrate on the [[Sky Bow]] missile.<ref name="Mistry2013">{{cite book|author=Dinshaw Mistry|title=Containing Missile Proliferation: Strategic Technology, Security Regimes, and International Cooperation in Arms Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9gTCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA97|date=20 June 2013|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0-295-80252-7|page=97}}</ref> There were calls to revive the program in response to China's missile threats during 1995 and 1996.<ref name="EdmondsTsai2004">{{cite book|author1=Martin Edmonds|author2=Michael Tsai|title=Taiwan's Security and Air Power: Taiwan's Defense Against the Air Threat from Mainland China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=69t_AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA101|date=23 November 2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-35053-7|page=101}}</ref> A senior Taiwanese official admitted that Taiwan was 'taken aback by China's moves', and there were fears that these could lead to an arms race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-03-21/news/mn-49672_1_theater-missile-defense/2 |title=China's Missile Launches Threaten to Trigger an Arms Race in Asia - Page 2 - latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=1996-03-21 |accessdate=2017-02-17}}</ref>
==General characteristics== * Length: > 20 metres * Propellant: Solid fuel<ref>{{cite book|title=Technologies underlying weapons of mass destruction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B4zSFd8DRWYC&pg=PA208|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-1-4289-2110-8|page=208}}</ref> * Range: Estimated 600 – 950km * Guidance: Inertial * Launch platform: Land-based *Payload: ~ 350kg<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nti.org/media/pdfs/design_characteristics_taiwan_ballistic.pdf?_=1366413773|format=PDF|title=Design Characteristics of Taiwan’s Ballistic Missiles|website=Nti.org|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref>
